{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}} {{Infobox lake | name = Chalan Beel | image = Chalan Beel Natore Bangladesh (7).JPG | caption = Chalan Beel in Natore District | location = [[Rajshahi Division]] | coords = {{coord|24.52|N|89.01|E|dim:50000_region:BD|display=inline,title}} | inflow = [[Atrai River]] and 46 others | basin_countries = Bangladesh | area = {{convert|26|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} | depth = {{convert|2|m|ft|abbr=on}} | max-depth = {{convert|4|m|ft|abbr=on}} }}
'''Chalan Beel''' ({{lang-bn|চলনবিল}}) is a [[wetland]] in Bangladesh. It is a large inland [[Depression (geology)|depression]], [[marsh]]y in character, with rich [[flora]] and [[fauna]]. Forty-seven rivers and other waterways flow into the Chalan Beel.<ref name = "Railways">{{cite book |last1=Srinivasan |first1=Roopa |last2=Tiwari |first2=Manish |last3=Silas |first3=Sandeep |date=2006 |title=Our Indian Railway: Themes in India's Railway History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O2-eHnajWxIC&pg=PA176 |location=New Delhi |publisher=Foundation Books |isbn=81-7596-330-1 |accessdate=29 November 2007}}</ref> As [[silt]] builds up in the [[beel]], its size is being reduced.<ref name=Banglapedia>{{cite book |last1=Alam |first1=Mohd Shamsul |last2=Hossain |first2=Md Sazzad |year=2012 |chapter=Chalan Beel |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Chalan_Beel |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref>
==Location and extent== [[File:BD Map Rivers of North Bengal2.jpg|thumb|left|Overview map showing Chalan Beel among the main rivers in North Bengal]] Chalan Beel is an extensive [[lowland]] area in the lower [[Atrai River|Atrai]] [[Drainage basin|basin]], and spreads across [[Singra Upazila|Singra]] and [[Gurudaspur Upazila|Gurudaspur]] [[upazila]]s on [[Natore District]], [[Chatmohar Upazila|Chatmohar]], [[Bhangura Upazila|Bhangura]] and [[Faridpur Upazila|Faridpur]] upazilas of [[Pabna District]], and [[Ullahpara Upazila|Ullahpara]], [[Raiganj Upazila|Raiganj]] and [[Tarash Upazila|Tarash]] upazilas of [[Sirajganj District]]. It consists of a series of [[beel]]s connected to one another by various [[canal|channels]] to form a continuous water body during the rainy season. Although the beel area expands into a vast water body with dense [[Aquatic plant|aquatic]] vegetation as long as the [[Jamuna River (Bangladesh)|Jamuna]] remains flooded during the [[monsoon]] months, it dries out in the winter months, leaving only patches of water in the central parts of this zone.<ref name = "IUCN">{{cite book |date=2002 |editor1-last=Nishat |editor1-first=Ainun |editor2-last=Huq |editor2-first=S. M. Inamul |editor3-last=Barua |editor3-first=Shuvasish P. |editor4-last=Reza |editor4-first=Ali A. H. M. |editor5-last=Khan |editor5-first=A. S. Monirazzaman |title=Bio-ecological zones of Bangladesh |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HT4p-7uG3cUC&pg=PA32 |publisher=International Union for Conservation of Nature Bangladesh Country Office |isbn=978-984-31-1090-9 |accessdate=29 November 2007}}</ref>
Chalan Beel is fast silting up. In the past it covered an area of about 1,085&nbsp;km² but was reduced to 368&nbsp;km² in 1909,<!--by 1909, or was there a reclamation project that year? The railways came in the early 1900s. I presume there must have been survey around that time but I am not getting the details.--> of which only 85&nbsp;km² remained underwater throughout the year. It has since shrunk to only 26&nbsp;km².<ref name = "Banglapedia"/>
==History== The most important factor dominating the river history in [[Bengal]] is the large proportion of silt carried by its rivers. It is the silt which has created the land and made it habitable by building it up through the centuries. It is silt which is fertilising the land, but the silt, which has been the most beneficial gift of nature, has also produced most of the river problems now confronting the people of Bengal. Silt deposited in the old river channel beds has forced them to change course, creating problems for abandoned areas while assisting in developing new areas.<ref>Majumdar, S.C., Chief Engineer, Bengal, ''Rivers of the Bengal Delta'', Government of Bengal, 1941, reproduced in ''Rivers of Bengal'', Vol I, 2001, p. 101, published by Education Department, Government of West Bengal.</ref>
The main volume of water from the [[Ganges River]] began flowing through the [[Padma River|Padma]] channel in the sixteenth century. Silt from the Padma helped in building up the southern portion of north Bengal. This is the most plausible explanation for the existence of a depression around Chalan Beel. The [[Teesta River|Teesta]] was active in the region until it changed its course in 1787. This territory lies in between the land raised in the north by the Teesta system when it was active and that in the south by the Padma.<ref>Majumdar, S.C., p. 46</ref>
However, there is another explanation for the creation of the depression. The Padma has been changing its course over the centuries. In Ven den Brouck's map of Bengal, prepared in 1660, the main channel of the Padma is shown as flowing through [[Faridpur District|Faridpur]]-[[Barisal District|Bakharganj]], but there also is a suggestion of another, possibly earlier channel. This channel runs through Rampur Boalia in [[Rajshahi Division|Rajshahi]], Chalan Beel, [[Dhaleswari River|Dhaleswari]] and [[Buriganga River|Buriganga]] before meeting the [[Meghna River|Meghna]]. At that time the [[Jamuna River (Bangladesh)|Jamuna]] was virtually non-existent and the [[Brahmaputra River|Brahmaputra]] used to flow through its old channel.<ref>Roy, Niharranjan, ''Bangalir Itihas, Adi Parba'', {{Bn icon}}, first published 1972, reprint 2005, p. 83, Dey’s Publishing, 13 Bankim Chatterjee Street, Kolkata, {{ISBN|81-7079-270-3}}</ref> {{Clear}}
{{multiple image | align = centre | direction = horizontal | header = Historical depictions of Chalan Beel | width = 200
| image1 = Van de Brook's map.jpg | alt1 = | caption1 = Van den Brouck's map of 1660
| image2 = 1776 Rennell - Dury Wall Map of Bihar and Bengal, India - Geographicus - BaharBengal-dury-1776.jpg | alt2 = | caption2 = James Rennell's map of 1776 }}
==Impact of railways== An estimate taken in 1945 found about 47 rivers and other waterways flowed into the Chalan Beel, a [[drainage basin|watershed]] of about {{convert|1547|sqmi|km2}}. In addition to being a [[Interchange (road)|crossroads]] for the many waterways it also served as the origin for the many rivers flowing south or east that eventually meet with the Padma or Jamuna. In the early 1900s, Chalan Beel began to be hemmed in by the construction of the [[Eastern Bengal Railway]] [[Chilahati-Parbatipur-Santahar-Darshana Line|main line]] on the west and the [[Santahar-Kaunia Line|Santahar-Bogra]] branch line on the north. The natural pattern of the water's drainage channels in this area were disrupted by the obstruction caused by the railway construction since railways in these low lands had to be built on [[Embankment (transportation)|embankments]].<ref name = "Railways"/>
==Flora and fauna== The banks of the beel are covered with dense stands of [[Saccharum spontaneum|kash]], [[Acacia nilotica|babla]], [[Arundo donax|nol]], [[Ipomoea|dhol kolmi]], [[Bombax ceiba|simul]], and [[Phoenix sylvestris|date palm]]. Seven species of frogs and one species of toad represent the amphibian fauna. Chalan Beel has a total of 34 species of reptiles include ten turtles and tortoises, nine lizards and various snake species. There are 27 species of mammals from 12 families.<ref name="IUCN"/>
==Pollution== Chalan Beel has experienced the negative effects of pesticide use in the surrounding farmlands. In 2010, Bangladesh Agricultural University research, found pesticide use has increased sixfold since 1982, and the fish population of Chalan Beel has halved in the same period. A 25 kilometre highway constructed on the Beel has divided into two and caused havoc on the fish breeding by disrupting their movement. Commercial [[overfishing]], grill and drag net and other destructive fishing have harmed the fish population.<ref>{{cite news |date=26 December 2010 |title=Bangladesh's once plentiful rivers run low on fish |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/bangladeshs-once-plentiful-rivers-run-low-on-fish-2169547.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |agency=Agence France-Presse |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722075535/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/bangladeshs-once-plentiful-rivers-run-low-on-fish-2169547.html |archive-date=22 July 2015 |accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref>
