[[File:The Multiverse and Galaxies at the Crawick Multiverse.JPG|alt=Stone rows on the North-South Line at the ''Crawick Multiverse''.|thumb|Landforms: Multiverse (foreground); Supercluster (centre); Milky Way and Andromeda Galaxy Mounds (behind).]]
'''''Crawick Multiverse''''' is a [[land art]] project by the landscape architect and designer [[Charles Jencks]] near [[Sanquhar]], [[Dumfries and Galloway]]. It opened to the public on 21 June 2015.<ref>Crawick Multiverse press release, and subsequent news reports: {{Cite web|url = http://www.crawickmultiverse.co.uk/new-scottish-multiverse-artland-is-out-of-this-world/|title = New £1m Scottish ‘Multiverse’ artland is out of this world|date = 2015-04-29|accessdate = 2015-04-30|website = Crawick Multiverse|publisher = |last = |first = }}
*{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-south-scotland-32530182|title = Charles Jencks Crawick coal mine art project nears completion|last = |first = |date = 2015-04-30|work = BBC|access-date = 2015-04-30|via = }}
*{{Cite news|url = http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/jencks-unveils-his-new-multiverse-of-2000-boulders-in-dumfries-and-galloway.124670750|title = Jencks unveils his new Multiverse of 2000 boulders in Dumfries and Galloway|last = Miller|first = Phil|date = 2015-04-30|work = heraldscotland|access-date = 2015-04-30|via = }}</ref> The project is located on the site of a former [[Open-pit mining|open cast coal mine]] and covers approximately 55 acres,<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url = http://www.crawickmultiverse.co.uk/about-crawick/|title = About Crawick|date = |accessdate = 2015-04-25|website = Crawick Multiverse|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> making it the largest of Jencks' works in Britain.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/uk/scotland/article4426571.ece|title = Old coal mine has cosmic facelift|last = Wade|first = Mike|date = 2015-04-30|work = The Times (London)|access-date = |via = }} [[Northumberlandia]], by comparison, covers 47 acres.</ref> Nine 'landforms' make up the ''Crawick Multiverse''. Like Jencks' other work, including the nearby ''[[Garden of Cosmic Speculation]]'', these represent ideas from modern cosmology.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url = http://www.crawickmultiverse.co.uk/|title = Home|date = |accessdate = 2015-04-25|website = Crawick Multiverse|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Unlike the ''Garden of Cosmic Speculation'', the ''Crawick Multiverse'' landforms use stone, in the style of the [[megalithic]] monuments. These include the 'North-South Line', a 400 meter long stone avenue flanked by over 300 boulders,<ref name=":0" /> and two [[stone circles]] on top of mounds representing the [[Milky Way]] and [[Andromeda Galaxy|Andromeda]] galaxies.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.crawickmultiverse.co.uk/crawick-multiverse-landforms/two-galaxy-mounds-andromeda-and-the-milky-way/|title = Two Galaxy Mounds – Andromeda and The Milky Way|date = |accessdate = 2015-04-25|website = Crawick Multiverse|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> In total, over 2000 boulders have been used in the project.<ref name=":0" /> Jencks has described it as "A cosmic landscape worthy of the ancients."<ref name=":1" />

